A cluster of birch trees stands here with their bark turned entirely black, the characteristic white peeling reduced to grey shreds that drift in the still air like flakes of dead skin.  The ground between them is carpeted with a dark, spongy mat of compressed leaves that squelch underfoot and release a sweet-rotten odour with every step.  Something has clawed deep furrows into the nearest trunk at shoulder height, the gouges still fresh enough to weep a thin amber sap.~
